<div id="review_357461320" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/357461320" />
    <a title="Gaby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7377335-gaby"><img alt="Gaby" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459025471p2/7377335.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/357461320?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gaby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gaby" href="/user/show/7377335-gaby">Gaby</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141399980" href="/book/show/11864960-disgrace">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer357461320" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5175802667719686402">I came across this in the airport. It was advertised as something for fans of ”The Killing” and the cover portrays a Sarah Lund lookalike. I thought some crime/detective thriller along the lines of the Millennium series was just what I needed: non-demanding yet engrossing. I didn&apos;t realize it was the 2nd book in a series until it was too late, so admittedly, perhaps I missed some crucial character development that would make ”Disgrace” more enjoyable. I disliked the cartoony, manichean villains </span>
  <span id="freeText5175802667719686402" style="display:none">I came across this in the airport. It was advertised as something for fans of ”The Killing” and the cover portrays a Sarah Lund lookalike. I thought some crime/detective thriller along the lines of the Millennium series was just what I needed: non-demanding yet engrossing. I didn't realize it was the 2nd book in a series until it was too late, so admittedly, perhaps I missed some crucial character development that would make ”Disgrace” more enjoyable. I disliked the cartoony, manichean villains and the fact that their evil habits (hunting) were described over and over in a very repetitive way, instead of maybe shedding some light into their motivations, histories, justifications or views on themselves. The ”hero”, Mørck, was more balanced, but I found his eternal judgements and complaints on everything (excluding Danish monarchy, which funnily enough escaped his otherwise omnipresent scathing criticism) very tiresome. But the most annoying bit was the ”comic relief” in the form of immigrant Assad: yes, we get it, he doesn't speak Danish perfectly, what an idiot, LOL. Other than a cliche both as a sidekick and as an immigrant, he didn't have any personality. The book developed in a typical and unoriginal way, the only unexpected thing being a display of corniness and sentimentality from a character that frankly I didn't care about. In other words... I struggled to get through this book, and by the end I kind of wished the bad guys would win. I'm giving it a 2 because not having read the first book might have been part of the problem... but I still think any book in a series should be able to sort of stand on its own.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5175802667719686402" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

