              <span id="reviewTextContainer2111413050" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7158922935900480621">5 Stars. Just as good as &quot;The Keeper&quot; although you can see the outline of what its all about early. Our hero, Detective Carl Morck, is just as difficult for the rest of the Copenhagen police department to deal with as he is in book #1. He&apos;s difficult on himself too! He plods through another cold case; he knows the likely suspects as well as the reader but he has trouble starting. Where&apos;s the link that ties them to the crime? Slowly Carl takes a little bit of information from here and another pie</span>
  <span id="freeText7158922935900480621" style="display:none">5 Stars. Just as good as "The Keeper" although you can see the outline of what its all about early. Our hero, Detective Carl Morck, is just as difficult for the rest of the Copenhagen police department to deal with as he is in book #1. He's difficult on himself too! He plods through another cold case; he knows the likely suspects as well as the reader but he has trouble starting. Where's the link that ties them to the crime? Slowly Carl takes a little bit of information from here and another piece from there, and then it all comes together. This entry in the series sees the addition of a third member to Department Q, such a disparate group. Rose Knudsen, a young graduate of the Academy, can't drive. Collectively, Carl, Assad and Rose must find the illusive street-person Kimmie and work through a twenty year old case of murder. Was Kimmie involved? Or were the culprits her friends - several of the leaders in today's Copenhagen society? Adler is such a great writer. A "must" read, but I suggest tackling these books in order, try "The Keeper" first. This one is so good that a re-read is clearly required. (Spring 2017)</span>
  <a data-text-id="7158922935900480621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


